{{Infobox religious building| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | name = Sumiyoshi Shrine | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image = {{image requested|cat=Azumino City}} | location = [[Nagano Prefecture|Nagano]], [[Azumino City|Azumino]], Misato-On 5932 | coordinates = {{Coord|36|16|6.39|N|137|52|46.95|E|scale:30000|display=inline}} | Deities = [[Sumiyoshi Sanjin]], [[Takeminakata|Takeminakata no Mikoto]], Hirohata Hachiman Ōkami | type = Former Prefectural Shrine | Established = | Main Hall = | Alias = | festival = [[Ofune Matsuri]] (April each year) | Rites = }} '''Sumiyoshi Shrine''' (住吉神社) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in [[Nagano Prefecture|Nagano]], [[Azumino City|Azumino]], Japan. Under the [[Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|modern shrine ranking system]], it was classified as a former Prefectural Shrine.
== Enshrined Deities == The shrine venerates five deities<ref>Nagano Prefecture Township Records, 1876</ref>: * [[Sumiyoshi Sanjin]]: ** Sokotsutsuo no Mikoto ** Nakatsutsuo no Mikoto ** Uwatsutsuo no Mikoto * [[Takeminakata|Takeminakata no Mikoto]] * Hirohata Hachiman Ōkami
== History == According to shrine tradition, the shrine was established during the eastern campaign of {{ill|Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|ja|坂上田村麻呂|12=draft|12=draft}}, and the subordinate shrine on the grounds enshrines {{ill|Sakanoue Tamura Myōjin|ja|坂上田村明神|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine became the total guardian of the 18 villages within the {{ill|Sumiyoshi-shō|ja|住吉荘|12=draft|12=draft}}, which was established through the donations of the local ruling Nishimaki clan when the {{ill|Chōkōdō|ja|長講堂|12=draft|12=draft}} manor was created. Originally, the shrine is said to have been located at the base of the ridge of Kakuzōzan Mountain in the {{ill|Karasu River (Nagano Prefecture)|ja|烏川|12=draft|12=draft}} gorge, where shrine priests and representatives of parishioners still climb during the Yoi Matsuri (Evening Festival). An {{ill|otabisho|ja|御旅所|12=draft|12=draft}} (temporary shrine) remains at Furushiroyama, where sacred horse rituals were performed the day after the annual festival.
During the {{ill|Chōtoku era|ja|長徳|12=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Shinano Provincial Governor|ja|信濃国司|12=draft|12=draft}} Fujiwara Koremasa renovated the shrine buildings. Records show that in 1567 (Eiroku 10), during the era of the {{ill|Takeda clan|ja|武田氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, parishioners contributed ten coins each to reconstruct the shrine buildings. During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine was maintained by residents of nearby villages such as Nire and Obiki, and the current shrine buildings date to 1786 (Tenmei 6). These are now designated as cultural properties of {{ill|Azumino City|ja|安曇野市|12=draft|12=draft}}.
In the {{ill|Bunroku era|ja|文禄|12=draft|12=draft}} land survey, the shrine's land holdings of seven koku were guaranteed, making it second only to the {{ill|Hotaka Shrine|ja|穂高神社|12=draft|12=draft}} within the Azumi District in terms of status. Additionally, in 1615 (Genwa 1), three tanbu of rice paddies were donated for new land development. Records from 1724 (Kyōhō 9) indicate that the shrine once had an expansive precinct measuring 2 chō and 48 ken east to west and 4 chō and 24 ken north to south (approximately 146,176 square meters).
Every April, the {{ill|Ofune Matsuri|ja|お船祭り|12=draft|12=draft}} is held, featuring the grand towing of a majestic festival float, or "ship."<ref>[https://www.city.azumino.nagano.jp/site/mizumonogatari/2491.html Ofune Matsuri of Kumano Shrine] - Azumino City</ref>
== Ofune Matsuri == The annual [[Ofune Matsuri]] (Ship Festival) in April is a vibrant celebration featuring a massive, ship-shaped float<ref>[https://www.city.azumino.nagano.jp/site/mizumonogatari/2491.html Azumino City Ofune Matsuri Information]</ref>.
== Cultural Properties == * '''Main Hall''' (Designated Tangible Cultural Property of Azumino City) * '''Historical Documents''' (Designated Tangible Cultural Property of Azumino City) * '''Ofune Matsuri''' (Designated Intangible Folk Cultural Property of Azumino City) * '''Shrine Forest''' (Designated Natural Monument of Azumino City) * '''Sacred Tree: Hinoki Cypress''' (Designated Natural Monument of Azumino City)
== location == * Nagano Prefecture, Azumino City, Misato-On 5932
== References == <references/>
== Further Reading == * ''Shinshu Culture Series: Temples and Shrines''. 1981. [[Shinano Mainichi Shimbun]]. * {{Cite book|author=Kenichi Tanigawa|title=Japanese Gods - Shrines and Sacred Sites, Vol. 9: Mino, Hida, Shinano|publisher=[[Hakusuisha]]|year=2000}}
== Related Articles == * [[Sumiyoshi Shrines in Japan]] * [[Ofune Matsuri]]
